msItem.title: Do bheirim barr búadha is áigh
msItem.incipit: Do bheirim barr búadha is áigh
msItem.explicit: ... o inber go bruach banna, futh no.

titleStmt.title: Do bheirim barr búadha is áigh

note.p: Black (0120830) gives this as a form of 'àite' but doesn't quite know what to make of it. Could it be a form of aiteamh as noted here?

The digitised HDSG Collection of Slips consists of the slips Ronald Black made for the HDSG and for himself. As is evident from this edition, the MS is damaged at this point. The digital slip (0120694) gives the headword slabhra and the quotation is ríoghsh[labhra] but it is written in the Notes section that no dictionary slip was made out [and thus that the] reading [is] conjectural.

The letter preceding the d is strange and I am not quite sure what to make of it. It appears to have iniditally been a character, now illegible, which was subsequently changed. The 'corrected' reading may be intended to be 'ui'
Black (0121092) created a slip for this point of the MS with the headword tairmeasgadh but no dictionary slip. There is no further information given in this slip.
The lenition marker is placed over the final t in this word but has been transcribed as after the c to render the ending -cht.
There are three HDSG slips for this, Black (0080817), (0130543), and (0110588\).
Black supplies the -in in the HDSG slip for "gath": (0002485).
Black supplies -in here in the quotation on the slip for dearbh (0060990).
Black (0110626) takes this as a form of ScG. oirthir whereas in this edition it is understood to be a form of the Early Gaelic airer.
